@node Debugging
@chapter Debugging

@cindex debugging
@cindex gdb
@cindex sdb
@cindex dbx
@cindex breakpoints
@cindex watch variables
@cindex call stack

xwpe integrates with external debuggers to provide a source-level
debugging environment.  You can set breakpoints, inspect variables,
step through code, and view the call stack --- all from within the
editor.

This chapter was verified against gdb 17.2 on 2026-05-28.

@section Debugger backends

@cindex debugger selection

xwpe supports three debugger backends, selectable via
@samp{Options @result{} Debugger} (@kbd{Alt-O D}):

@table @strong
@item gdb (GNU Debugger)
The default and recommended backend.  Supports all debugging features.
xwpe detects gdb by matching the @code{(gdb)} prompt in the debugger's
output (see @code{we_debug.c}).

@item sdb (Symbolic Debugger)
Legacy UNIX debugger.  Not available on modern Linux systems.

@item dbx
Berkeley UNIX debugger.  Available on some BSD and commercial UNIX
systems.
@end table

On modern Linux, only gdb is relevant.  The other backends exist for
historical compatibility.

@section Compiling for debugging

Before debugging, compile with debug symbols:

@example
# In the project file or compiler options:
CMPFLAGS = -g -O0
@end example

The @code{-g} flag includes debug information.  @code{-O0} disables
optimisation, which ensures that variables and control flow match the
source code.

@section Starting the debugger

@table @kbd
@item Ctrl-F10 / Ctrl-G R
Start the debugger (or continue if already running).  xwpe launches
gdb as a child process, loads the executable, and waits for commands.

@item Ctrl-F2 / Ctrl-G Q
Quit the debugger.
@end table

When the debugger stops (at a breakpoint, after a step, or on a
signal), xwpe marks the current line in the source code and opens
the file if it is not already open.

@section Breakpoints

@cindex breakpoints
@cindex Ctrl-F8
@cindex toggle breakpoint

@table @kbd
@item Ctrl-F8 / Ctrl-G B
Toggle a breakpoint at the current line.  The line is highlighted
to indicate the breakpoint.

@item Ctrl-G M
Remove all breakpoints.
@end table

Breakpoints persist across debug sessions within the same xwpe
session.  If a project file is open, breakpoints are saved and
restored with the project.

@section Stepping through code

@cindex stepping
@cindex trace
@cindex step over
@cindex F7
@cindex F8

@table @kbd
@item F7 / Ctrl-G S (Trace)
Execute the next source line.  If the line contains a function call,
step @emph{into} the function.

@item F8 / Ctrl-G N (Step)
Execute the next source line.  If the line contains a function call,
step @emph{over} it (execute the entire function and stop at the next
line in the current function).

@item Ctrl-G G (Goto cursor)
Execute until the line at the cursor position is reached.

@item Ctrl-G F (Finish function)
Execute until the current function returns.
@end table

@section Watch variables

@cindex watch window
@cindex Ctrl-F7
@cindex variable inspection

The Watch Window displays the values of selected variables.  Values
are updated each time the debugger stops.

@table @kbd
@item Ctrl-F7 / Ctrl-G W
Add a variable to the watch list.  A dialog prompts for the variable
name or expression.

@item Ctrl-G E
Edit a watched variable expression.

@item Ctrl-G D
Delete a watched variable.

@item Alt-D A
Remove all watched variables.
@end table

Inside the Watch Window:
@itemize @bullet
@item Use cursor keys to navigate between variables.
@item Press @key{Return} to edit the selected variable.
@item Press @key{Insert} to add a new variable at the current position.
@item Press @key{Delete} to remove the selected variable.
@end itemize

If a variable is not in scope (e.g.@: a local variable in a function
that has not been called), xwpe displays a warning.

@section Call stack

@cindex stack window
@cindex Ctrl-F6
@cindex backtrace

@table @kbd
@item Ctrl-F6 / Ctrl-G K
Open the Stack Window, showing the call chain from @code{main()} to
the current function.
@end table

The Stack Window is read-only.  Use cursor keys to navigate and
@key{Return} to jump to a frame in the source code.

If a signal is caught inside a system function (e.g.@: @code{read()}),
the stack shows the first visible user function instead.

@section Displaying output

@table @kbd
@item Ctrl-G O
Display the program's output window.  This shows the text output of
the debugged program.  (Not available in X11 mode --- use a separate
terminal.)
@end table

@section Debugger mode

@samp{Options @result{} Debugger} also offers a choice between:

@table @strong
@item Full-screen mode
The debugger uses the full terminal; xwpe and the debugger share
the screen.

@item Normal mode
The debugger runs in a separate terminal or window.
@end table

On modern systems, full-screen mode is the typical choice.

@section Example debugging session

This example assumes a C program compiled with @code{-g}:

@enumerate
@item
Open the source file: @command{wpe debug_test.c}

@item
Set a breakpoint on @code{main()}: move the cursor to the
@code{int x = 5;} line and press @kbd{Ctrl-F8}.

@item
Start the debugger: press @kbd{Ctrl-F10}.  gdb launches and stops
at the breakpoint.

@item
Inspect a variable: press @kbd{Ctrl-F7}, type @code{x}, press
@key{Return}.  The Watch Window shows @code{x = 5} (or an
uninitialised value if the line has not executed yet).

@item
Step to the next line: press @key{F8}.  The cursor advances.

@item
Step into a function: press @key{F7} on a line with a function call.
The cursor moves into the called function.

@item
View the call stack: press @kbd{Ctrl-F6}.  The Stack Window shows
the chain of function calls.

@item
Continue execution: press @kbd{Ctrl-F10}.  The program runs until
the next breakpoint or until it exits.

@item
Quit the debugger: press @kbd{Ctrl-F2}.
@end enumerate

@section Known issues

@itemize @bullet
@item
Debugging leaks memory.  The exact source of the leak is unknown and
has been present since the Payne era.

@item
The sdb and dbx backends are untested on modern systems and may not
work.

@item
The debugging environment requires the programming-mode binary
(@command{wpe} or @command{xwpe}), not the editor-only binary
(@command{we} or @command{xwe}).
@end itemize

